<Layout title="Combustible Cladding on Brisbane Buildings: What Unit Sellers Need to Know | Daniel Gierach Property" description="If your apartment building is on the QBCC combustible cladding register, it affects what you must disclose, how buyers finance the purchase, and what remediation costs the body corporate may face." draft={draft}>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Combustible Cladding on Brisbane Buildings: What Unit Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        If your building is on the QBCC cladding register, disclosure is mandatory, lender restrictions apply, and body corporate remediation costs could affect your sale. Here is what to check before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Combustible cladding became a serious concern in Australia following a series of high-profile fires in buildings clad with aluminium composite panels (ACP), most notably the Grenfell Tower fire in the United Kingdom in 2017 and the Lacrosse building fire in Melbourne in 2014. Queensland responded with legislation requiring building owners to register affected buildings, conduct risk assessments, and in many cases undertake rectification works. If you own a unit in a mid-rise or high-rise building in Brisbane, this may affect your sale in ways that are not immediately obvious.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which buildings are affected</h2>
      <p>The Queensland combustible cladding requirements primarily apply to buildings of Type A or Type B construction that were built or significantly renovated between 1994 and 2019. In practice, this means mid-rise and high-rise apartment buildings, typically those of three or more storeys. Most low-rise townhouse complexes and detached houses are not affected by these requirements.</p>

      <p>The relevant cladding material is aluminium composite panels with a polyethylene core, commonly known as ACP or ACM. This material was used extensively in building facades during the period in question because it was lightweight, affordable, and aesthetically versatile. The problem is that the polyethylene core is highly combustible and can cause fire to spread rapidly across the exterior of a building.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The QBCC combustible cladding register</h2>
      <p>The Queensland Building and Construction Commission (QBCC) maintains a public register of buildings that have been identified as potentially affected by combustible cladding. Building owners of affected buildings were required to register with the QBCC and undertake a staged assessment process involving a risk assessment by a qualified fire engineer and, where required, remediation works.</p>

      <p>The register is publicly searchable. Anyone can look up a building's address and see whether it has been registered, what stage of the assessment process it is at, and whether rectification works are required or have been completed. If you are a unit owner considering selling, checking the register is the first step. Your body corporate manager should also be able to confirm the building's status and provide any relevant documentation from the assessment process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What you must disclose when selling</h2>
      <p>Under Queensland property law, sellers are required to disclose material facts that a buyer would reasonably want to know before entering a contract. Combustible cladding is clearly a material fact in any building where it is present or where the issue is under assessment. Specifically:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.75rem;">
        <li>If the building is registered on the QBCC combustible cladding register, this must be disclosed to the buyer.</li>
        <li>If the body corporate has received a notice, report, or engineer's assessment relating to cladding, this is also disclosable.</li>
        <li>If rectification works have been ordered or are planned, and the associated costs will affect the body corporate's finances (potentially through a special levy), buyers need to know.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The disclosure happens via the seller's solicitor in the conveyancing process. Your solicitor will request the body corporate records, which will include any cladding-related documentation. The buyer's solicitor reviews these records as part of their due diligence. However, surprises that emerge during that process can kill deals. Proactive disclosure up front is always better than allowing a buyer to discover an issue mid-contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How cladding issues affect buyer financing</h2>
      <p>This is where the practical impact on your sale becomes most acute. Some lenders in Australia have implemented restrictions on lending for properties in buildings with unresolved combustible cladding issues. The restrictions vary by lender and by the severity of the cladding assessment, but they can include:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.75rem;">
        <li>Outright refusal to lend on the property until remediation is certified as complete.</li>
        <li>Reduced loan-to-value ratios, meaning buyers need a larger deposit.</li>
        <li>Conditions requiring the buyer to demonstrate the body corporate has a remediation plan and adequate funding in place.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If your building is on the register and remediation is incomplete, the pool of buyers who can finance the purchase is smaller. Some buyers who are pre-approved in principle will discover that their specific lender will not approve the loan once the building's cladding status becomes clear. This is a real risk in a transaction and sellers in affected buildings need to price and market accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Body corporate costs and special levies</h2>
      <p>Rectifying combustible cladding is expensive. Costs vary significantly depending on the building's size, the extent of affected cladding, the complexity of the replacement work, and whether scaffolding or other access requirements drive up the price. For a mid-rise building, remediation costs can run into hundreds of thousands of dollars, which the body corporate must fund.</p>

      <p>If the building has not yet levied owners for rectification costs, a prospective buyer faces potential special levy exposure after settlement. Even if the body corporate has an approved plan, understanding the timeline and the likely levy impact is part of a reasonable buyer's due diligence. Buyers who discover this exposure after going unconditional are unlikely to be happy, and disputes over non-disclosure are unpleasant and expensive for everyone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do before listing</h2>
      <p>If you own a unit in a building that may be affected, take these steps before you engage an agent or set a listing date:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.75rem;">
        <li>Search the QBCC combustible cladding register for your building's address. The register is free to access online.</li>
        <li>Contact your body corporate manager and ask for the current status of any cladding assessment, any rectification orders, and the body corporate's plan and timeline for remediation.</li>
        <li>Ask whether any special levies have been raised or are anticipated in relation to cladding rectification, and for what amounts.</li>
        <li>Provide all of this information to your solicitor before contracts go out, so that appropriate disclosure is made from the outset.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The worst outcome is a buyer who signs contracts, orders a body corporate records search, discovers the cladding issue and associated levy exposure, and either attempts to withdraw or demands a price reduction. Transparent disclosure upfront eliminates that risk and attracts buyers who have accepted the position before committing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buildings where remediation is complete</h2>
      <p>If your building has completed its rectification works and received the relevant clearances from the QBCC, the position changes materially. A building with a documented clean bill of health on cladding is in a much stronger position than one where the issue is unresolved. If your building has reached this point, ensure your body corporate manager can provide the relevant certificates and that your solicitor includes them in the pre-contract disclosure. This is a positive selling point, not something to leave buyers to discover themselves.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.8;"><strong style="color:#f5d07a;">Selling a unit in Brisbane's inner east?</strong> Daniel can help you understand what buyers will ask and how to position a sale in a building with a disclosure requirement. <a href="/contact" style="color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">Get in touch.</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

